[3] Region: mobilize survivors
Date: Wed 10 Dec 2014
Source: Medical News Today [edited]
http://www.medicalnewstoday.com/articles/286740.php


Mobilize survivors to contain Ebola, experts argue
--------------------------------------------------
The mobilization of Ebola survivors is necessary to hasten containment of the epidemic. That is the key message of an editorial published in the International Journal of Epidemiology. Ebola survivors could be valuable blood [plasma] donors. Their antibodies may have protective properties and could also improve the chances of survival in those infected with Ebola.

4 main reasons why Ebola survivors are critical to controlling the Ebola epidemic are listed in the editorial by Dr. Zena Stein of the HIV Center for Clinical and Behavioral Studies at the New York State Psychiatric Institute and Joseph Mailman School of Public Health at Columbia University and her colleagues, who are based at the HIV Center for Clinical and Behavioral Studies at the New York State Psychiatric Institute and Columbia University.

1) People who have recovered from their infection have developed immunity to the current strain of Ebola, which makes them able to care for sick people with little to no risk of becoming infected again. "In a sense survivors are the only people in the world who are 'vaccinated' against further Ebola infection with the strain in circulation," says Dr. Stein. "This uniquely positions them to mediate between the infected and uninfected and between local people and foreign responders."

2) Survivors could be valuable blood [plasma] donors. Their antibodies may have protective properties and could also improve the chances of survival in those infected with Ebola. However, research has not yet proved the effectiveness of this kind of immunotherapy using the blood of survivors.

3) There is a cultural dynamic behind the authors' 3rd reason. Ebola survivors in afflicted countries often speak local languages, and communities may be more receptive to their aid than foreign responders. The authors consider that their cultural position would allow Ebola survivors to care in both medical and home-based settings. In addition, training and employment as caregivers would allow Ebola survivors to have an important source of income during a period that has seen increasing poverty and Ebola-related stigmatization.

4) Survivors may be able to generate a vital community-based response to the epidemic. "Community-initiated actions in epidemics are recognized as important to public health, and have already been proven successful in an African context. For instance, the Treatment Action Campaign in South Africa has generated an effective, nationwide social movement among those HIV-positive, stigmatized and deprived of treatment. A movement among Ebola survivors could establish their effectiveness as advocates and educators, countering stigma and building community trust." ... -- more

[Byline: David McNamee]

